The crash is caused by an off-by-one heap allocation bug in `first_field()`.

At the crashing line:

```c
out[n] = '\0';
```

the program writes one byte past the end of the heap allocation.

## Walkthrough of the program state

`main()` sets:

```c
const char *line = "alice,bob,carol\n";
char *first = first_field(line);
```

So inside `first_field()`:

```c
static char *first_field(const char *line) {
```

`line` points to the string literal:

```text
"alice,bob,carol\n"
```

The characters are:

```text
index:  0 1 2 3 4 5 ...
char:   a l i c e , ...
```

Then:

```c
const char *comma = strchr(line, ',');
```

`strchr()` finds the first comma, which is at `line + 5`.

So:

```c
comma == line + 5
```

Next:

```c
size_t n = comma ? (size_t)(comma - line) : strlen(line);
```

Because `comma` is non-NULL:

```c
n = comma - line;
n = 5;
```

This means the first field has length 5: `"alice"`.

Then the code allocates:

```c
char *out = (char *)malloc(n);
```

Since `n == 5`, this allocates exactly 5 bytes.

Valid indexes in `out` are therefore:

```text
out[0], out[1], out[2], out[3], out[4]
```

Then:

```c
memcpy(out, line, n);
```

This copies 5 bytes:

```text
'a', 'l', 'i', 'c', 'e'
```

That part is valid because it writes exactly 5 bytes into a 5-byte allocation.

But then:

```c
out[n] = '\0';
```

Since `n == 5`, this writes:

```c
out[5] = '\0';
```

That is one byte past the allocated buffer. The allocation only has indexes `0` through `4`.

So AddressSanitizer reports:

```text
Heap buffer overflow
```

The defect is here:

```c
char *out = (char *)malloc(n);
```

The function is trying to return a C string, but a C string needs space for both the characters and the terminating null byte. The allocation needs to be `n + 1` bytes, not `n` bytes.

This bug is not specific to the input `"alice,bob,carol\n"`. It also happens when there is no comma:

```c
size_t n = strlen(line);
char *out = malloc(n);
memcpy(out, line, n);
out[n] = '\0';   // still one byte past the allocation
```

It can also be especially problematic for an empty field, e.g. `",bob"`:

```c
n = 0;
out = malloc(0);
out[0] = '\0';   // invalid because no byte was allocated
```

##### Recommendation

Minimal local fix:

```c
static char *first_field(const char *line) {
    const char *comma = strchr(line, ',');
    size_t n = comma ? (size_t)(comma - line) : strlen(line);

    char *out = malloc(n + 1);
    if (!out) {
        return NULL;
    }

    memcpy(out, line, n);
    out[n] = '\0';

    return out;
}
```

More thorough root-cause fix, including overflow and NULL-input handling:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdint.h>

static char *first_field(const char *line) {
    if (line == NULL) {
        return NULL;
    }

    const char *comma = strchr(line, ',');
    size_t n = comma ? (size_t)(comma - line) : strlen(line);

    if (n == SIZE_MAX) {
        return NULL; // prevent overflow in n + 1
    }

    char *out = malloc(n + 1);
    if (out == NULL) {
        return NULL;
    }

    memcpy(out, line, n);
    out[n] = '\0';

    return out;
}

int main(void) {
    const char *line = "alice,bob,carol\n";
    char *first = first_field(line);

    if (first == NULL) {
        fprintf(stderr, "failed to parse first field\n");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("first = %s\n", first);
    free(first);
    return 0;
}
```

The essential fix is to allocate `n + 1` bytes because the returned buffer is a null-terminated string.

